    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen using exrc=true on my windows machine, I am prompted to manually trust the .nvim.lua file, as designed.\nI press v, then focus the buffer, run :trust \nI checked the trust database file, it contains the correct sha256 and path of the trusted file. On Windows it's located at `C:\\Users\\<Me>\\AppData\\Local\\nvim-data\\trust`\n\nWhen I close and reopen neovim in the same directory, I get prompted again to trust the file, and the file's code doesn't execute.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. In `C:\\Users\\<Me>\\AppData\\Local\\nvim` create a minimal init.lua with the following contents\n```\n-- init.lua\nvim.o.exrc = true\n```\n\n2. Create a temporary directory (eg at `C:\\Users\\<Me>\\nvim-repro`) with the following .nvim.lua file inside of it\n```\n-- .nvim.lua\nprint(\"It works!\")\n```\n\n3. cd into `C:\\Users\\<Me>\\nvim-repro` and run `nvim` or `nvim .` (both commands have the same problem)\n4. This shows up, press v\n```\nexrc: Found untrusted code. To enable it, choose (v)iew then run `:trust`:                                                                                                                C:\\Users\\<Me>\\nvim-repro\\.nvim.lua\n```\n5. The .nvim.lua file opens in an horizontal split on top of an empty buffer. Focus is on the .nvim.lua buffer by default. Run :trust which gives output\n```\nAllowed in trust database: \"<path>\"\n```\n6. Quit vim (challenge: impossible)\n7. Reopen vim with `nvim` or `nvim .` in the same directory\n8. Prompt reappears and the debug\n\nVerification steps : \n1. Run `sha256 -t .nvim.lua` and look at the hash\n2. then `cat C:\\Users\\<Me>\\AppData\\Local\\nvim-data\\trust` which should contain the filepath and the same exact hash\n\nWorkarounds tried : \nIn the trust file manually replacing path delimiters with either `\\\\` or `/` does not fix the issue\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOn step 8 : prompt shouldn't reappear and the user should see \"It Works!\" printed.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-1042+g27bc7dcb01\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11 Pro Version 10.0.26100 Build 26100\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal 1.22.12111.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nEmpty\n\n### Installation\n\nFrom bob-nvim",
