            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I also encountered the issue, and I've added a couple of debug prints. What I found is that the computed hash in the `secure.read` function differs from what is in `secure.trust`. At the same time, the one in `secure.trust` is valid (verified with an external tool).\n\nAfter further investigation, the `contents` in the `secure.read` had `\\n` as end-of-line characters, while in `secure.trust` it was `\\r\\n`.\nMy `.nvim.lua` file has the filetype set to `dos` and contains:\n```lua\nvim.opt.fileformat = \"dos\"\nvim.opt.fixendofline = false\n```\nAfter forcing `set filetype=unix` for this file, the trust mechanism works as expected. However, it works until the next change, then it switches to `dos` (as specified in the config). \n\nAnyway, it looks like the `compute_hash` does not correctly handle endlines.",
